<exercise checkit-seed="0004" checkit-slug="V8" checkit-title="Polynomial and matrix spaces">
  <statement>
      <p>Consider the following statement.</p>
        <ul><li> The set of
                matrices <m>\left\{ \left[\begin{array}{cc}
3 &amp; -2 \\
1 &amp; 1
\end{array}\right] , \left[\begin{array}{cc}
3 &amp; -2 \\
1 &amp; 1
\end{array}\right] , \left[\begin{array}{cc}
5 &amp; -5 \\
1 &amp; 1
\end{array}\right] , \left[\begin{array}{cc}
16 &amp; -14 \\
4 &amp; 4
\end{array}\right] \right\}</m>
                
                spans <m>\mathrm{M}_{2,2}</m>.
        </li></ul>
    <ol>
        <li> Write an equivalent statement using a matrix equation.</li>
        <li> Explain why your statement is true or false.</li>
    </ol>
  </statement>
  <answer>
      <p><me>\mathrm{RREF}\,\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
3 &amp; 3 &amp; 5 &amp; 16 \\
-2 &amp; -2 &amp; -5 &amp; -14 \\
1 &amp; 1 &amp; 1 &amp; 4 \\
1 &amp; 1 &amp; 1 &amp; 4
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 &amp; 2 \\
0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 &amp; 2 \\
0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0
\end{array}\right]</me></p>
     <ol>
         <li>
                     The matrix equation <me>y_{1} \left[\begin{array}{cc}
3 &amp; -2 \\
1 &amp; 1
\end{array}\right] + y_{2} \left[\begin{array}{cc}
3 &amp; -2 \\
1 &amp; 1
\end{array}\right] + y_{3} \left[\begin{array}{cc}
5 &amp; -5 \\
1 &amp; 1
\end{array}\right] + y_{4} \left[\begin{array}{cc}
16 &amp; -14 \\
4 &amp; 4
\end{array}\right]=B</me> has a solution for every <m>B \in \mathrm{M}_{2,2}</m>.
          </li>
          <li>
              The set of matrices <m>\left\{ \left[\begin{array}{cc}
3 &amp; -2 \\
1 &amp; 1
\end{array}\right] , \left[\begin{array}{cc}
3 &amp; -2 \\
1 &amp; 1
\end{array}\right] , \left[\begin{array}{cc}
5 &amp; -5 \\
1 &amp; 1
\end{array}\right] , \left[\begin{array}{cc}
16 &amp; -14 \\
4 &amp; 4
\end{array}\right] \right\}</m>
                     does not span
                     <m>\mathrm{M}_{2,2}</m>.
          </li>
      </ol>
  </answer>
</exercise>
